Yes, the "loop" approach is natively baked right into OpenSpec’s core design.  
You do not need to configure anything extra or hack the system to make them work together.  
In fact, OpenSpec was specifically created to fix the biggest problem of the AI "loop" (often called agentic or loop engineering)—agent amnesia and downstream hallucinations.  
Here is exactly how OpenSpec handles the loop natively and how it integrates with your favorite CLI tools like Claude Code.  

1. How OpenSpec Implements the "Loop" Natively. In traditional agentic development, the loop looks like this:  
Prompt → Code → Error/Test Fail → Fix → Repeat. 
The issue is that if the loop runs for too long, the AI forgets the original goal, goes off on tangents, or creates messy, circular bug-fixing loops.  
OpenSpec changes the loop by introducing Spec-Driven Development (SDD). It structures the loop into a deterministic cycle using its OPSX workflow:  

[Propose/Explore] ──> [Design & Tasks] ──> [Apply (The Code Loop)] ──> [Archive]
       ▲                                            │
       └─────────────────── Iterate ────────────────┘

Instead of looping blindly on code, the AI loops on intent first, and then tightly loops on execution:

The "Explore/Propose" Loop: You run /opsx:propose. The AI loops through your existing code and specs, asks probing questions, and refines a Markdown document until you both agree on what to build.

The "Apply" Loop: When you run /opsx:apply, the agent is locked into a highly structured, execution-focused loop. It reads tasks.MD executes a task, checks it off, runs a test or a validation compiler, handles the error if it fails, and moves to the next task.

Because OpenSpec forces the AI to write down its plan (tasks.md, design.md) on your local disk, the context persists. If Claude Code crashes or hits a token limit mid-loop, you don't lose progress. You just start a new session, and the agent reads the filesystem to pick up exactly where the loop left off.

2. Do You Need to Configure Anything?  
No heavy configuration is needed. OpenSpec is designed to be a lightweight, tool-agnostic layer that sits natively on top of your existing AI CLIs and IDEs.  
When you initialize OpenSpec in your repository, it automatically hooks into your environment:

```bash
# 1. Install globally
npm install -g @fission-ai/openspec@latest

# 2. Initialize in your project root
cd your-project
openspec init
``` 
Running openspec init sets up the /openspec or @openspec structures and registers the native slash commands (or "skills") that your AI tools recognize.  
How it seamlessly fits into your current tools: Claude Code: It integrates natively via slash commands.  
When you are inside Claude Code, you can type /opsx:propose or /opsx:apply directly. 
Claude reads the filesystem artifacts as its ground truth.  
Cursor / Windsurf: It utilizes your .cursorrules or workspace settings. The AI agent reads the active OpenSpec directories to understand the codebase context automatically.  

Pro Tip for Loop Engineering: OpenSpec relies on your project's "Constitution". After running openspec init, open openspec/project.md and explicitly define your tech stack, testing framework, and linting rules. 
When the AI goes into its execution loop, it will use those boundaries to validate its own code, preventing the loop from breaking.  

