If you want an incredibly clean root directory, you can take your custom coding style guidelines and move them into openspec/project.md. Because OpenSpec strictly forces Claude to read the /openspec directory at the start of every loop, Claude will respect your custom rules perfectly, leaving your root CLAUDE.md short, sweet, and focused purely on environment commands.  


> OpenSpec takes care of the token economy too? Or do we need to add complementary resources such as RTK and Caveman skill?  

OpenSpec handles input context token economics at an architectural level, but it serves a very different purpose than tools like RTK (Rust Token Killer) and the Caveman skill.

They are highly complementary. To minimize costs, many developers stack OpenSpec together with these skills.

The differences in how they tackle token optimization determine whether you should use them as complements.  

1. What OpenSpec Handles Natively (The Input Loop)
OpenSpec tackles the most expensive type of token drain: agentic amnesia and long-tail context bloat.
  * Scope Reduction: Instead of your CLI agent parsing your entire repository over and over again during a loop, OpenSpec abstracts the work into isolated specifications (tasks.md and delta specs).
  * Preventing "Loop Bleeding": The most common way agents burn through hundreds of dollars is by getting stuck in an error loop (e.g., fixing a bug, causing another bug, reverting, etc.). By using strict verification blocks, OpenSpec stops the loop early if a task fails validation, saving you thousands of wasted iteration tokens.

OpenSpec optimizes intent and state memory, ensuring you spend your input tokens purely on focused execution.

2. Why You Need Complementary Tools (RTK & Caveman)
While OpenSpec manages the structural flow, it does not compress raw command-line outputs or force the model to be linguistically brief. This is where RTK and Caveman act as specialized plug-ins:  

🛠️ RTK (Rust Token Killer): 
   * What it does: It intercepts noisy terminal command outputs (like a giant verbose test suite runner, NPM logs, or grep dumps) and strips out the noise, sending only the actionable failures to the AI.  
   * Why pair it with OpenSpec: During the /opsx:apply phase, OpenSpec forces the agent to execute tests and lint commands. Pairing it with RTK ensures that when OpenSpec runs a test command, the agent isn't flooded with 100,000 tokens of passing logs.

🪨 Caveman Skill: 
   * What it does: It optimizes output tokens by stripping out pleasantries, hedging, and conversational fluff ("Sure! I can help you with that..."), forcing Claude to reply in ultra-concise fragments while preserving exact code and technical terms.  
   * Why pair it with OpenSpec: OpenSpec doesn't stop Claude from being overly polite or chatty when summarizing what it did. Caveman forces the output to be minimal, which drastically cuts down on the generation cost during long sessions.  

The Verdict: The Ultimate Loop Stack

For the absolute tightest token economy in Claude Code or OpenCode, the community favorite workflow is to combine them:

1. OpenSpec: Manages the architectural state and keeps the agent from losing its mind or looping blindly.

2. RTK: Shrinks the logs and terminal data fed into the /opsx loop execution.

3. Caveman: Shrinks the words Claude uses to talk back to you.  

You can watch the Caveman Token Optimization Guide to see how reducing conversational fluff cuts down on Claude Code output tokens without impacting technical accuracy.

> It is reliable to add openspec in a previous project that doesn't use openspec initially. Can I, from this moment on pass to use openspec to evolve the project?  


Yes, it is highly reliable. In fact, OpenSpec's philosophy was explicitly built to handle "brownfield" (pre-existing) codebases just as fluidly as brand-new ones. You do not need to pause your project or manually write documentation for your entire historical codebase before you start.

You can safely initialize OpenSpec right now and use it to evolve your project moving forward.  

1. How OpenSpec Handles Pre-Existing Projects Natively:
   The entire framework relies on a concept called Delta Specs.
   When you want to add a new feature to your old project, OpenSpec doesn't need a complete manual of your whole system. It only maps out what is changing right now.
   Even better, OpenSpec has a built-in onboarding feature explicitly for this scenario:  
   ```bash
   # Inside your existing tool (e.g., Claude Code), run:
   /opsx:onboard  
   ```  
   What /opsx:onboard does:
   Instead of you having to document the past, the AI will use this skill to run a preflight scan of your existing codebase. It will automatically reverse-engineer your code, learn your tech stack, figure out your folder structure, and generate your core global repository context (project.md) for you.  

2. The Step-by-Step Way to Evolve Your Project From Today
To safely transition your legacy project into the OpenSpec workflow, use this frictionless, step-by-step strategy:

Step 1: Initialize and Onboard
Run the initialization in your project root and let the AI map out your current state.
```bash
npm install -g @fission-ai/openspec@latest
cd your-existing-project
openspec init  
```  
(Now open Claude Code or your preferred assistant)  
```bash
> /opsx:onboard
```  

Step 2: Use "Explore Mode" for your first new feature
Because the AI doesn't know your old code perfectly yet, do not rush straight into coding. Start with Explore Mode, which acts as a no-stakes brainstorming partner:  
```plaintext
> /opsx:explore "Add a JWT refresh token mechanism to our old auth router"
```  
The agent will actively crawl your existing files, ask you probing questions about how your old code works, point out architectural quirks, and work with you until the implementation plan is fully locked down.  

Step 3: Propose, Apply, and Archive
Once you and the AI agree on the plan, let the standard OpenSpec loop take over:

/opsx:propose creates the new isolated change folder containing tasks.md, design.md, and the spec delta.

/opsx:apply forces Claude Code to strictly execute and check off the tasks inside your old codebase.

/opsx:archive completes the task, moving the logs to your archive and automatically building up your openspec/specs/ directory.


The Long-Term Benefit: Natural Evolution:  
By taking this approach, your documentation grows organically with your code. You don't waste days writing specs for features you aren't touching. Every time you use the /opsx loop to fix a bug or add a route, OpenSpec captures that small piece of the puzzle. Over a few weeks, your legacy project naturally builds a comprehensive, pixel-perfect specification library that keeps future AI agents completely aligned.  

